prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Again, this obsevation mainly aims detection of continuum emission. The three spectral windows are employed for the continuum observations, which cover about 5.6 GHz range.
Line: The typical velocity width of the GMCs in M33 is 5-10 km/s (Miura et al. 2010). The spectral window resolution, 0.6km/s is chosen because it is closer the typical velocity width of parsec scale clouds inside a GMC (e.g., Higuchi et al. 2009).
We set all GMCs at the same system velocity in OT, so that it does not need to change for each pointing. The velocity of the GMCs spans from -250 to -110 km/s, corresponding to ~55MHz difference in the sky frequencies. This is still within the bandwidth of that spw (468.75MHz) of CO line.

The typical size of the cluster is 15 pc (e.g. Battinelli et al. 1996). We set the angular resolution of 2 arcsec, corresponding to 8 pc, which is comparable to the cluster size. Also, it is enough to resolve the typical size of the GMCs in M33, 50-<200 pc (Miura et al. 2012).
Largest angular scale: The maximum size of stellar clusters in M33 is 46 pc (11arcsec) in M33, while the typical size of the GMC in M33 is 80 pc (~20 arcsec) (Miura et al. 2012). We set the largest angular scale of 20 arcsec as the maximum number of these values.
The structures have size ~<20 arcsec, so detection is assured for all cases.

Please note that this observation mainly aims to detect 100 GHz-band continuum emission, so time estimation is driven by continuum, not line.
The expected peak flux density for the M33 HII regions is 0.4-8mJy at 100 GHz (see Science Justification). We request the sensitivity of 0.1 mJy/beam for 4-80 S/N detection.
The aggregateBandWidth for time estimation is set to effective bandwidth of three spectral windows of 7.5GHz * 3/4 = 5.625GHz, excluding one spectral window for CO line. We do not include the rest of spw (for CO line) to achive our science goal because it is not emission free.
Based on above conditions, our science goal can be achived with 3.2 hours observations in total.
Line detection: According to the Sensitivity Calculator, the sensitivity will achieve 26 mJy at 1 km/s resolution with the integration time of 1.51 min (corresponds to the time on source per pointing). The typical velocity width and molecular mass of the M33 GMC are 5-10km/s and 0.8-7.4 times 10^6 solar masses (Miura et al. 2010). The expected flux density is 0.8-6.3 Jy with a velocity resolution of 1 km/s. We expect detect CO line emission with 30-200 signal-to-noise ratio.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose simultaneous 100-GHz radio continuum and CO(1-0) observations at 8 pc resolution toward HII regions associated with 75 Giant Molecular Clouds (GMCs) in the nearby spiral galaxy M33, with the purpose of searching for obscured young clusters and probe the distribution of the surrounding molecular gas. The 100-GHz radio continuum emission in star-forming galaxies is expected to be strongly dominated by the free-free bremsstrahlung component due to ionizing radiation from massive young stars, and can reveal such population of obscured young clusters. Although many studies on external galaxies have used 24micron emission as a tracer of obscured star formation, its spatial resolution is limited to 6 arcsec, insufficient to compare with molecular gas studies at sub-arcsec resolution. With these data, we will generate a catalog of obscured star clusters within the GMCs as well as the density structure of these GMCs, and then calculate their sizes, masses and accurate star formation efficiencies. We will check the validity of obtaining the star formation rates (SFR) from the continuum emission by comparing with classical SFR measurements.
